I think I’m done on my soapbox, but if anyone wants to hop up on theirs feel free to reply

I’m writing my capstone on dungeons and dragons, and my professors/cohort think it’s COOL, even if it’s not traditional. And they’re excited that I’m doing it because it’s something I love!!

There are contemporary works worth studying alongside the canon! Nontraditional and all!

And if ur a teacher, rejoice in ur students finding stories they love!

Telling ur students that genres they love are “unacademic” just tells them that their interests are irrelevant. Don’t wonder why kids hate to read when they have to read stories they hate

Because it doesn’t matter what genre you like or what authors you think are just the bees knees, your interests are important and can be as “academic” as you’d like them to be. 

Stop gate keeping an art form based on vague guideline made by dead people decades ago.

But it’s not okay to tell someone that the stories they love aren’t worth consuming or studying. It’s not fair to demean genres that you don’t enjoy. 

If you love to read King or Tolkien or Gaiman (I do!), then keep pursuing the stories you love.

Literature can be more than just an art you appreciate. The stories we read shape us, and they can change the world. 

Read the stories that you love to read. Those are the ones that will change you. If that’s Shakespeare, that’s awesome!

The canon is not the end all be all of literary studies. I can appreciate it, but I can’t say in good conscience that a bunch of dead, old, white dudes define the academic field I’ve decided to dedicate seven years of my life to.

I had a professor in undergrad who so ardently hated fantasy that she would often call it “unacademic” to study it. 

That didn’t stop me from writing my capstone on a fantasy series, but it did tell me that the reason I loved literature so much wasn’t good enough to merit study

To presume that literature that only appeals to adults is the only kind worth studying is to suggest that adulthood is the only important part of the human experience worth studying. It demeans the importance of childhood and young adult experiences. 

Same thing with genres.

Dude if the only thing I ever read was Shakespeare, I wouldn’t be getting my MA in cultural studies. 

Art is important, all of it. And literature and stories have a special way of connecting us to our own experiences and humanity.
I’ve been in this young adult lit class, and I’m so tired of hearing that genres like fantasy, YA lit, children’s lit, etc are not considered to be “academic” enough
